com.foreach.across.modules.web.ui.elements

Class ViewElementGenerator<ITEM,VIEW_ELEMENT extends ViewElement>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.foreach.across.modules.web.ui.elements.ViewElementGenerator<ITEM,VIEW_ELEMENT>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MutableViewElement, ViewElement, Iterable<VIEW_ELEMENT>

    public class ViewElementGenerator<ITEM,VIEW_ELEMENT extends ViewElement>
extends Object
implements Iterable<VIEW_ELEMENT>, MutableViewElement
    Represents a collection of ViewElement instances that are generated based on a template or callback method and an input item. The special case about this implementation is that the elements are only generated once they are requested using the iterator(), whereas a normal ContainerViewElement requires all members to be set before hand.

    Use this class if you want to configure a template in the form of either a ViewElement or ViewElementBuilder and provide a set of domain objects for which the template should be customized. It is generally safer to use a ViewElementBuilder as that will always create new ViewElement instances instead of modifying the existing one.

    If a ViewElement is used as item template, the generator is not thread-safe and the same element will be run and possibly modified through every iteration.

    Exactly one ViewElement will be generated for every domain object. It is allowed for the generated element to be null - which will cause it not be rendered. However please be aware that the item will still be present in the iterator and size() and isEmpty() calls will consider those as valid elements.

    Like the ContainerViewElement, a ViewElementGenerator does not add any additional output, it only renders its children.
